@article{WOS086,
abstract = {Aims$\backslash$nBiodiversity-ecosystem function experiments can test for causal$\backslash$nrelationships between planting diversity and community productivity.$\backslash$nPlanting diversity is routinely introduced as a design element in$\backslash$ncreated wetlands, yet substantive support for the finding that early$\backslash$ndiversity positively affects ecosystem functioning is lacking for$\backslash$nwetlands. We conducted a 2-year diversity-productivity experiment using$\backslash$nfreshwater wetland mesocosms to investigate community biomass production$\backslash$nas affected by planted macrophyte functional richness.$\backslash$nMethods$\backslash$nA richness gradient of macrophytes in four emergent wetland plant$\backslash$nfunctional groups was established in freshwater mesocosms for two$\backslash$nconsecutive years. Species-specific aboveground morphological traits of$\backslash$nplant size were measured at peak growth in both years; rooting depth was$\backslash$nmeasured for each species in the second year. Aboveground biomass (AGB)$\backslash$nand belowground biomass (BGB) were harvested after peak growth in the$\backslash$nsecond year; first year AGB was estimated from morphological traits in$\backslash$nconstructed regression equations. Net richness effects (i.e. both$\backslash$ncomplementarity effects and selection effects) were calculated using an$\backslash$nadditive partitioning method.$\backslash$nImportant Findings$\backslash$nSpecies richness had a positive effect on community AGB relative to$\backslash$nmonocultures in the first year. In the second year, mean AGB was$\backslash$nsignificantly reduced by competition in the most species-rich mixtures$\backslash$nand all mixtures underyielded relative to the average monoculture.$\backslash$nCompetition for soil resources was weaker belowground, whereby root$\backslash$ndistribution at depths {\textgreater} 20 cm was reduced at the highest richness$\backslash$nlevels but overall BGB production was not affected. Changes in species$\backslash$nbiomass were strongly reflected by variation in species morphological$\backslash$ntraits, and species above and belowground performances were highly$\backslash$ncorrelated. The obligate annual (Eleocharis obtusa), a dominant$\backslash$ncompetitor, significantly contributed to the depression of perennial$\backslash$nspecies' growth in the second growing season. To foster primary$\backslash$nproductivity with macrophyte richness in early successional communities$\backslash$nof created wetlands where ruderal strategies are favored and competition$\backslash$nmay be stronger than species complementarity, unsystematic planting$\backslash$ndesigns such as clustering the same or similar species could provide$\backslash$nprotection for some individuals. Additionally, engineering design$\backslash$nelements fostering spatial or temporal environmental variability (e. g.$\backslash$nmicrotopography) in newly created wetlands helps diversify the responses$\backslash$nof wetland macrophyte species to their environment and could allow for$\backslash$ngreater complementarity in biomass production.},
